</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[820,1432,1077,2077]" lastBlockId="7.[156,767,197,320]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[846,961,1923,1947]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Etymology</emphasis>
.Th e speci c epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saba &amp; Iwao &amp; Fujita" authorityYear="2012" box="[1197,1325,1923,1947]" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Disasterina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="akajimaensis">
<emphasis box="[1197,1325,1923,1947]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">akajimaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from the island of Akajima, where the 
<typeStatus box="[1244,1333,1955,1979]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected. New Japanese names given for this genus and species are Numeri-itomaki-hitode-zoku and Akajima-numeriitomaki-hitode, respectively. Akajima is the locality, while in Japanese “numeri” refers to the slimy nature of the body surface, an “itomaki” is a spool used in sewing with a shape that looks like asterinid sea stars, “hitode” are seastars, and “zoku” means genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
